Patient appointments are represented by the business concept “Appointment,” defined as a scheduled encounter between a patient and a provider for clinical services. The retrieved context says appointments can be in-person office visits, telehealth consultations, or procedural sessions.

In the schema, this is implemented by the APPOINTMENTS table, whose purpose is to store patient appointment scheduling and encounter information. Appointments are scheduled and tracked in that table through:
the patient, provider, and optionally department links via patient_id, provider_id, and department_id;
the scheduled date and time via appointment_date and appointment_time;
the appointment classification via appointment_type;
the planned length via duration_minutes;
the current state via appointment_status;
and, when relevant, the reason for cancellation via cancellation_reason.

The context also says appointment status types include scheduled, confirmed, checked-in, in-progress, completed, canceled, and no-show. Appointment types are defined as classifications based on purpose, duration, and resource requirements, with examples including new patient evaluation, established patient follow-up, annual wellness visit, procedure, and imaging.

The APPOINTMENTS table further connects the appointment to core healthcare entities through foreign keys to PATIENTS, providers, and departments. PATIENTS is the patient master record table, storing demographic and administrative information for the patient identified by patient_id.

For historical tracking at the data level, APPOINTMENTS includes valid_from and valid_to, and the glossary defines this as historization using effective dating to reconstruct historical states over time. It also includes is_deleted, which aligns with the glossary’s soft delete concept, where records are marked inactive rather than physically removed.

So, based strictly on the retrieved context, patient appointments are scheduled and tracked in APPOINTMENTS by recording who the appointment is for, who will conduct it, where it is associated organizationally, when it is scheduled, what type of encounter it is, how long it is expected to last, what its current status is, and any cancellation reason.
